messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Output

- Full HTTP request path: /cms/admin/group
- Are all HTTP methods acceptable? False
- HEAD: False
- POST: True
- OPTIONS: True
- TRACE: False
- GET: False
- PUT: False
- DELETE: False
- PATCH: False

Explanation

- Path derivation:
  - The create_group endpoint is defined in app/api/cms/admin.py under the admin blueprint (admin_api) with the route "/group".
  - The admin blueprint is registered under the CMS blueprint with url_prefix="/admin" in app/api/cms/__init__.py.
  - The CMS blueprint is registered on the app with url_prefix="/cms" in app/__init__.py.
  - Therefore, the full path for this endpoint is /cms/admin/group.
  - There are no path parameters for this endpoint.

- Accepted HTTP methods:
  - The decorator for create_group is @admin_api.route("/group", methods=["POST"]), so only POST is explicitly supported.
  - Consequently, “all methods” is not acceptable (False), and only POST is acceptable (True).

- Method-specific checks based on code behavior:
  - HEAD: Not explicitly allowed (only POST is listed). In Flask, HEAD is not automatically added for non-GET methods, so HEAD would not be served by this route (False).
  - POST: Explicitly allowed (True).
  - OPTIONS: Flask automatically handles OPTIONS for routes and will advertise allowed methods; thus considered acceptable (True).
  - TRACE: Not implemented (False).
  - GET: Not allowed (False).
  - PUT: Not allowed (False).
  - DELETE: Not allowed (False).
  - PATCH: Not allowed (False).

In summary, the endpoint is /cms/admin/group, supports only POST, with OPTIONS implicitly supported, HEAD/GET/PUT/DELETE/PATCH/TRACE not supported by this route.
